# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: over-the-air-updates
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Multivariate testing or multinomial testing is similar to A/B testing but may test more than two versions at the same time or use more controls.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Simple A/B tests are not valid for observational, quasi-experimental or other non-experimental situations—commonplace with survey data, offline data, and other, more complex phenomena.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] "A/B testing" is a shorthand for a simple randomized controlled experiment, in which a number of samples (e.g.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] A and B) of a single vector-variable are compared.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] A/B tests are widely considered the simplest form of controlled experiment, especially when they only involve two variants.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] However, by adding more variants to the test, its complexity grows.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] A company has a customer database of 2,000 people and launches an email campaign with a discount code in order to generate sales through its website.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] The company creates two versions of the email with different calls to action (the part of the copy that encourages customers to act—in the case of a sales campaign, make a purchase) and identifying promotional codes.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] The company then monitors which campaign has the higher success rate by analyzing the use of the promotional codes.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] The email using the code A1 has a 5% response rate (50 of the 1,000 people emailed used the code to buy a product), and the email using the code B1 has a 3% response rate (30 of the recipients used the code to buy a product).
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] The company therefore determines that in this instance, the first call to action is more effective and will use it in future sales.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] A more nuanced approach would involve applying statistical testing to determine whether the differences in response rates between A1 and B1 were statistically significant (highly likely that the differences are real, repeatable and not the result of random chance).
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] In the previous example, the purpose of the test is to determine the more effective strategy to encourage customers to make a purchase.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] If, however, the aim of the test had been to determine which email would generate the higher clickthrough rate (the percentage of people who actually click the link after receiving the email), the results might have been different.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] For example, even though more of the customers receiving the code B1 accessed the website, because the call to action did not state the end date of the promotion, many recipients may feel no urgency to make an immediate purchase.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Consequently, if the purpose of the test had been simply to determine which email would bring more traffic to the website, the email containing code B1 might well have been more successful.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] An A/B test should have a defined, measurable outcome, such as sales converted, clickthrough rate or registration rate.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Two-sample hypothesis tests are appropriate for comparing the two samples in which the samples are divided by the two control cases in the experiment.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Z-tests are appropriate for comparing means under stringent conditions regarding normality and a known standard deviation.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Student's *t*-tests are appropriate for comparing means under relaxed conditions when less is assumed.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Welch's *t*-test assumes the least and is therefore the most commonly used two-sample hypothesis test in which the mean of a metric is to be optimized.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] While the mean of the variable to be optimized is the most common choice of estimator, others are regularly used.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Fisher's exact test can be employed to compare two binomial distributions, such as a click-through rate.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] A/B tests most commonly apply the same variant (e.g., user interface element) with equal probability to all users.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] However, in some circumstances, responses to variants may be heterogeneous.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] While a variant A might have a higher response rate overall, variant B may have an even higher response rate within a specific segment of the customer base.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] In this case, while variant A attracted a higher response rate overall, variant B actually elicited a higher response rate with men.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] As a result, the company might select a segmented strategy as a result of the A/B test, sending variant B to men and variant A to women in the future.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] If segmented results are expected from the A/B test, the test should be properly designed at the outset to be evenly distributed across key customer attributes, such as gender.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] The test should contain a representative sample of men vs. women and assign men and women randomly to each “variant” (variant A vs. variant B).
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Failure to do so could lead to experiment bias and inaccurate conclusions.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] This segmentation and targeting approach can be further generalized to include multiple customer attributes rather than a single customer attribute—for example, customers' age and gender—to identify more nuanced patterns that may exist in the test results.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] The results of A/B tests are simple to interpret to create a clear picture of real user preferences, as they directly test one option over another.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] A/B tests can also provide answers to highly specific design questions.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] One example of this is Google's A/B testing with hyperlink colors.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] In order to optimize revenue, Google tested dozens of hyperlink hues to determine which colors attract the most clicks.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] A/B tests are sensitive to variance; they require a large sample size in order to reduce standard error and produce a statistically significant result.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] In applications in which active users are abundant, such as with popular online social-media platforms, obtaining a large sample size is trivial.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] In other cases, large sample sizes are obtained by increasing the experiment enrollment period.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] However, using a technique coined by Microsoft as Controlled Experiment Using Pre-Experiment Data (CUPED), variance from before the experiment start can be taken into account so that fewer samples are required to produce a statistically significant result.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Because of its nature as an experiment, running an A/B test introduces the risk of wasted time and resources if the test produces unwanted or unhelpful results.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] In December 2018, representatives with experience in large-scale A/B testing from 13 organizations (Airbnb, Amazon, Booking.com, Facebook, Google, LinkedIn, Lyft, Microsoft, Netflix, Twitter, Uber and Stanford University) summarized the top challenges in a paper.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] The challenges were grouped into four areas: analysis, engineering and culture, deviations from traditional A/B tests and data quality.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] It is difficult to definitively establish when A/B testing was first used.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] The first randomized double-blind trial to assess the effectiveness of a homeopathic drug occurred in 1835.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Experimentation with advertising campaigns, which has been compared to modern A/B testing, began in the early 20th century.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] The advertising pioneer Claude Hopkins used promotional coupons to test the effectiveness of his campaigns.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] However, this process, which Hopkins described in his 1923 book *Scientific Advertising*, did not incorporate concepts such as statistical significance and the null hypothesis, which are used in statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Modern statistical methods for assessing the significance of sample data were developed separately in the same period.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] This work was conducted in 1908 by William Sealy Gosset when he altered the Z-test to create Student's *t*-test.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] With the growth of the internet, new ways to sample populations have become available.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Google engineers ran their first A/B test in 2000 to determine the optimum number of results to display in its search-engine results.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] The first test was unsuccessful because of glitches that resulted from slow loading times.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Later A/B testing research was more advanced, but the foundation and underlying principles generally remain the same, and in 2011, Google ran more than 7,000 different A/B tests.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] In 2012, a Microsoft employee working on the search engine Bing created an experiment to test different methods of displaying advertising headlines.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Within hours, the alternative format produced a revenue increase of 12% with no impact on user-experience metrics.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Today, major software companies such as Microsoft and Google each conduct over 10,000 A/B tests annually.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] A/B testing has been claimed by some to be a change in philosophy and business-strategy in certain niches, although the approach is identical to a between-subjects design, which is commonly used in a variety of research traditions.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] A/B testing as a philosophy of web development brings the field into line with a broader movement toward evidence-based practice.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Many companies now use the "designed experiment" approach to making marketing decisions, with the expectation that relevant sample results can improve positive conversion results.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] It is an increasingly common practice as the tools and expertise grow in this area.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] As a result, more marketing teams now use A/B testing to guide decisions, matching the rigor of the test to measured hypotheses and measuring impact on outcomes such as conversions, revenue, and downstream conversion.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] A/B tests have been used by large social-media sites such as LinkedIn, Facebook and Instagram to understand user engagement and satisfaction of online features, such as a new feature or product.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] A/B tests have also been used to conduct complex experiments on subjects such as network effects when users are offline, how online services affect user actions and how users influence one another.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] On an e-commerce website, the purchase funnel is typically a helpful candidate for A/B testing, as even marginal decreases in drop-off rates can represent a significant gain in sales.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Significant improvements can be sometimes seen through testing elements such as copy text, layouts, images and colors.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] In these tests, users only see one of two versions, as the goal is to discover which of the two versions is preferable.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] A/B testing can be used to determine the right price for a product, which is one of the most difficult challenges faced when a new product or service is launched.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] A/B testing (especially valid for digital goods) is an effective mechanism to identify the price point that maximizes the total revenue.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] A/B tests have also been used by political campaigns.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] In 2007, Barack Obama's presidential campaign used A/B testing to garner online attraction and understand what voters wanted to see from Obama.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] For example, Obama's team tested four distinct buttons on their website that led users to register for newsletters.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] Additionally, the team used six different accompanying images to attract users.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] A/B testing is commonly employed when deploying a newer version of an API.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] For real-time user experience testing, an HTTP layer 7 reverse proxy is configured in such a way that *n*% of the HTTP traffic is routed to the newer version of the backend instance, while the remaining *100-n*% of HTTP traffic hits the (stable) older version of the backend HTTP application service.
[src:over-the-air-updates/a-b-testing] This is usually achieved to limit the exposure of customers to a newer backend instance such that, if there is a bug with the newer version, only *n*% of the total user agents or clients are affected while others are routed to a stable backend, which is a common ingress control mechanism.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] A precise and stable characteristic feature is that no or not all functions of embedded software are initiated/controlled via a human interface, but through machine-interfaces instead.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Manufacturers build embedded software into the electronics of cars, telephones, modems, robots, appliances, toys, security systems, pacemakers, televisions and set-top boxes, and digital watches, for example.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] This software can be very simple, such as lighting controls running on an 8-bit microcontroller with a few kilobytes of memory with the suitable level of processing complexity determined with a Probably Approximately Correct Computation framework (a methodology based on randomized algorithms).
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] However, embedded software can become very sophisticated in applications such as routers, optical network elements, airplanes, missiles, and process control systems.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Unlike standard computers that generally use operating systems such as macOS, Windows or Linux, embedded software may use no operating system.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] When they do use one, a wide variety of operating systems can be chosen from, typically a real-time operating system.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Code for embedded software is typically written in C or C++, but various high-level programming languages, such as C#, Java, Python and JavaScript, are now also in common use to target microcontrollers and embedded systems.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Assembly languages are often used too, especially in booting and interrupt handling.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Ada is used in some military and aviation projects.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Most consumers are familiar with application software that provide functionality on a computer.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] However embedded software is often less visible, but no less complicated.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Unlike application software, embedded software has fixed hardware requirements and capabilities, and addition of third-party hardware or software is strictly controlled.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Embedded software needs to include all needed device drivers at manufacturing time, and the device drivers are written for the various hardware devices.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] The software is highly dependent on the CPU and specific chips chosen.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Most embedded software engineers have at least a passing knowledge of reading schematics, and reading data sheets for components to determine usage of registers and communication system.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Conversion between decimal, hexadecimal and binary is useful as well as using bit manipulation.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Web applications are often used for managing hardware, although XML files and other output may be passed to a computer for display.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] File systems with folders are typically used, however SQL databases are often absent.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Software development requires use of a cross compiler, which runs on a computer but produces executable code for the target device.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Debugging requires use of an in-circuit emulator, and debugging hardware such as JTAG or SWD debuggers.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Software developers often have access to the complete kernel (OS) source code.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Size of the storage memory and RAM can vary significantly.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Some systems run in 16 KB of Flash and 4 KB of RAM with a CPU operating at 8 MHz, other systems can rival contemporary computers.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] These space requirements lead to more work being done in C or embedded C++, instead of C++.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Interpreted languages like BASIC (while e.g.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Parallax Propeller can use compiled BASIC) and Java (Java ME Embedded 8.3 is available for e.g.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] ARM Cortex-M4, Cortex-M7 microcontrollers and older ARM11 used in Raspberry Pi and Intel Galileo Gen.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] 2) are not commonly used; while an implementation of the interpreted Python 3 language – MicroPython – is however available expressly for microcontroller use, e.g.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] 32-bit ARM-based (such as BBC micro:bit) and 16-bit PIC microcontrollers.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Communications between processors and between one processor and other components are essential.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Besides direct memory addressing, hardware level common protocols include I²C, SPI, serial ports, 1-Wires, Ethernets, and USB.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Communications protocols designed for use in embedded systems are available as closed source from companies including InterNiche Technologies and CMX Systems.
[src:over-the-air-updates/embedded-software] Open-source protocols stem from uIP, lwip, and others.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] An **over-the-air update** (or **OTA update**), also known as **over-the-air programming** (or **OTA programming**), is an update to an operating system, or to firmware for an embedded system, that is delivered through a wireless network, such as Wi-Fi or a cellular network.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] These systems include mobile phones, tablets, set-top boxes, cars and telecommunications equipment.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] OTA updates for cars and internet of things devices can also be called **firmware over-the-air** (**FOTA**).
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Various components may be updated OTA, including the device's operating system, applications, configuration settings, or parameters like encryption keys.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] The term *over-the-air update* applies to embedded systems.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Before OTA updates, embedded devices could only be flashed through direct physical access (with a JTAG) or wired connections (usually through USB or a serial port).
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] It is also used for mobile devices such as smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Over-the-air delivery may allow updates to be distributed at larger scales, reduce the cost of delivering updates, or increase the rate of adoption of these updates.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] The distributor of these updates can decide whether users are allowed to decline these updates, and may choose to disable certain features on end-user devices until an update is applied.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Users may be unable to revert an update after it is installed.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] OTA updates are designed to be as small as possible in order to minimize energy consumption, network usage, and storage space.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] This is achieved by only transferring the differences between the old firmware and the new firmware, rather than transmitting the entire firmware.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] A delta of the old and new firmware is produced through a process called diffing; then, the delta file is distributed to the end-device, which uses the delta file to update itself.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] On smartphones, tablets, and other devices, an over-the-air update is a firmware or operating system update that is downloaded by the device over the internet.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Previously, users had to connect these devices to a computer over USB to perform an update.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] These updates may add features, patch security vulnerabilities, or fix software bugs.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] The two main mobile operating systems are iOS and Android.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] iOS gained support for over-the-air updates in iOS 5. iOS updates are distributed exclusively by Apple, resulting in wide availability and relatively high adoption rates.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Major iOS releases are usually installed on 60%–70% of iPhones within a few months of release.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Android OTA updates are device-dependent, and are not distributed by Google but by device manufacturers and sometimes wireless carriers.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] This has led to inconsistent availability of updates, and to Android fragmentation.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] In the past, fragmentation increased the complexity of developing third-party apps for Android due to inconsistent availability of the latest software frameworks on users' phones, and led to security concerns due to delays in the distribution of security updates.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Project Mainline significantly lowers the role of middlemen in delivering OTA updates.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Since Android 8.0, Android OTA updates follow an A/B partition scheme, in which an update is installed to a second ("B") partition in the background, and the phone switches to that partition the next time it is rebooted, reducing the time taken to install updates.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Windows Phone OTA updates were usually distributed by OEMs such as Nokia, and sometimes wireless carriers.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] OTA updates for Windows Phone devices labelled Microsoft Mobile were usually distributed by Microsoft.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Cars can support OTA updates to their in-car entertainment system, navigation map, telematic control unit, or their electronic control units (the onboard computers responsible for most of the car's operation).
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] In cars, the telematic control unit is in charge of downloading and installing updates, and OTA updates are downloaded through cellular networks, like smartphones.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Cars cannot be driven while an OTA update is being installed.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Before an update, the car checks that the update is genuine, and after the update completes, it verifies the integrity of all affected systems.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] In the past, Volkswagen had to recall 11 million vehicles to fix an issue with its cars' emissions control software, and other manufacturers have instituted recalls due to software bugs affecting the brakes, or the airbags, requiring all affected customers to travel to dealership to receive updates.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] OTA updates would have removed the need to go through dealerships, leading to lower warranty costs for manufacturers and lower downtime for customers.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] OTA updates also allow manufacturers to deploy potential new features and bug fixes more quickly, making their cars more competitive in the market, and resulting in an increased pace of product improvements for consumers.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] For example, OTA updates can deliver improvements to a car's driver assistance systems and improve the car's safety.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] However, OTA updates can also present a new attack vector for hackers, since security vulnerabilities in the update process could be used by hackers to remotely take control of cars.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Hackers have discovered such vulnerabilities in the past, and many car manufacturers have responded by instituting vulnerability disclosure programs (a.k.a. bug bounty programs).
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Attack vectors specific to OTA updates include "spoofing, tampering, repudiation [attacks], information leakage, denial-of-service," replay attacks, and privilege escalation attacks.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Sensor nodes are often located in places that are either remote or difficult to access.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] As an example, Libelium has implemented an OTA programming system for Zigbee WSN devices.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] This system enables firmware upgrades without the need of physical access, saving time and money if the nodes must be re-programmed.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] OTA is similar to firmware distribution methods used by other mass-produced consumer electronics, such as cable modems, which use TFTP as a way to remotely receive new programming, thus reducing the amount of time spent by both the owner and the user of the device on maintenance.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Over-the-air provisioning (OTAP) is also available in wireless environments (though it is disabled by default for security reasons).
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] It allows an access point (AP) to discover the IP address of its controller.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] When enabled, the controller tells the other APs to include additional information in the Radio Resource Management Packets (RRM) that would assist a new access point in learning of the controller.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] It is sent in plain text however, which would make it vulnerable to sniffing.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] The similar term *over-the-air service provisioning* (OTASP) specifically refers to the wireless initial provisioning ("activation") of a phone.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] During activation, a mobile phone is provisioned with parameters like its phone number, mobile identification number, and system ID, granting it initial access to the cellular network.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] OTASP is sometimes called *over-the-air activation* or *over-the-air bootstrapping*.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] The alternative to OTA bootstrapping is SIM bootstrapping, where the phone reads the network settings stored on a SIM card.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] SIM bootstrapping has limitations: settings stored on a SIM card may become stale between the time the SIM is manufactured and the time it is used; also, some phones (and other cellular client equipment) do not use SIM cards.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] Various standards bodies have issued OTA provisioning standards.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] In 2001, the WAP Forum published the WAP Client Provisioning standard.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] After the Open Mobile Alliance subsumed the WAP Forum, this standard became known as OMA Client Provisioning (OMA CP).
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] In OMA CP, phones are provisioned by "invisible" SMS messages sent by the cellular network, which contain the requisite settings.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] OMA CP was followed by a newer standard, OMA Device Management (OMA DM), which use a different form of SMS-based provisioning (called "OMA Push").
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] OMA DM sessions are always client-initiated.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] The "invisible" SMS does not contain configuration settings; instead, it tells the phone (the "DM Client") to connect to a DM Server (operated by the cellular network provider); once connected, the DM Server sends configuration commands to the client.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] There are a number of standards that describe OTA functions.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] One of the first was the GSM 03.48 series.
[src:over-the-air-updates/firmware-over-the-air] The Zigbee suite of standards includes the Zigbee Over-the-Air Upgrading Cluster which is part of the Zigbee Smart Energy Profile and provides an interoperable (vendor-independent) way of updating device firmware.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] A **patch** is data for modifying an existing software resource such as a program or a file, often to fix bugs and security vulnerabilities.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] To *patch* is also the process of applying the data to the existing resource.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Patching a system involves applying a patch.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] A patch may be created to improve functionality, usability, or performance.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] A patch may be created manually, but commonly it is created via a tool that compares two versions of the resource and generates data that can be used to transform one to the other.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Typically, a patch needs to be applied to the specific version of the resource it is intended to modify, although there are exceptions.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Some patching tools can detect the version of the existing resource and apply the appropriate patch, even if it supports multiple versions.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] As more patches are released, their cumulative size can grow significantly, sometimes exceeding the size of the resource itself.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] To manage this, the number of supported versions may be limited, or a complete copy of the resource might be provided instead.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Patching allows for modifying a binary executable.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Although this can be technically challenging (requires a thorough understanding of the workings of the executable), it may be feasible when the source code is unavailable to build a full executable, and it allows for a smaller distribution which can be more economical than distributing full files.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Although often intended to fix problems, a patch can introduce new problems – a scenario called software regression.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] In some cases, an update intentionally disables functionality, for instance, by removing aspects for which the consumer is no longer licensed.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Patch management is a part of lifecycle management, and involves a strategy and planning of what patches should be applied to which systems and at what times.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Typically, a patch is applied in a permanent way (i.e. to storage), but in some cases, a patch is applied to memory (i.e. via a tool such as a debugger) in which case the change is lost when the resource is reloaded from storage.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Software update is sometimes conflated with patch even though they are not synonyms.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] An update can be implemented using patch files and the patching process.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Also, some may contend that patching is not limited to modifying file content – that adding, removing and replacing whole files is patching.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Typically, patch connotates a relatively small change, so a patch that is large in size or scope may be called the more general *software update* or another more specific name such as service pack.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Windows NT and its successors (including Windows 2000, Windows XP, Windows Vista and Windows 7) use *service pack*.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Historically, IBM used the terms *FixPak* and *Corrective Service Diskette* for such updates.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Historically, software suppliers distributed patches on paper tape or on punched cards, expecting the recipient to cut out the indicated part of the original tape (or deck), and patch in (hence the name) the replacement segment.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Later patch distributions used magnetic tape.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Then, after the invention of removable disk drives, patches came from the software developer via a disk or, later, CD-ROM via mail.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] With widely available Internet access, downloading patches from the developer's web site or through automated software updates became often available to the end-users.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Starting with Apple's Mac OS 9 and Microsoft's Windows ME, PC operating systems gained the ability to get automatic software updates via the Internet.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Computer programs can often coordinate patches to update a target program.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Automation simplifies the end-user's task, allowing them to only execute an update program, whereupon that program makes sure that updating the target takes place completely and correctly.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Service packs for Microsoft Windows NT and its successors and for many commercial software products adopt such automated strategies.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Some programs can update themselves via the Internet with very little or no intervention on the part of users.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] The maintenance of server software and of operating systems often takes place in this manner.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] In situations where system administrators control a number of computers, this sort of automation helps to maintain consistency.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] The application of security patches commonly occurs in this manner.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] With the advent of larger storage media and higher Internet bandwidth, it became common to replace entire files (or even all of a program's files) rather than modifying existing files, especially for smaller programs.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Patches for proprietary software are typically distributed as executable files instead of source code.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] When executed these files load a program into memory which manages the installation of the patch code into the target program(s) on disk.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Patches for other software are typically distributed as data files containing the patch code.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] These are read by a patch utility program which performs the installation.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] This utility modifies the target program's executable file—the program's machine code—typically by overwriting its bytes with bytes representing the new patch code.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] If the new code will fit in the space (number of bytes) occupied by the old code, it may be put in place by overwriting directly over the old code.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] If the new code is bigger than the old code, the patch utility will append load record(s) containing the new code to the object file of the target program being patched.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] When the patched program is run, execution is directed to the new code with branch instructions (jumps or calls) patched over the place in the old code where the new code is needed.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] On early 8-bit microcomputers, for example the Radio Shack TRS-80, the operating system includes a PATCH/CMD utility which accepts patch data from a text file and applies the fixes to the target program's executable binary file(s).
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] The patch code must have place(s) in memory to be executed at runtime.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Inline patches are no difficulty, but when additional memory space is needed the programmer must improvise.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Naturally if the patch programmer is the one who first created the code to be patched, this is easier.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Savvy programmers plan in advance for this need by reserving memory for later expansion, left unused when producing their final iteration.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Other programmers not involved with the original implementation, seeking to incorporate changes at a later time, must find or make space for any additional bytes needed.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] The most fortunate possible circumstance for this is when the routine to be patched is a distinct module.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] In this case the patch programmer need merely adjust the pointers or length indicators that signal to other system components the space occupied by the module; he is then free to populate this memory space with his expanded patch code.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] If the routine to be patched does not exist as a distinct memory module, the programmer must find ways to shrink the routine to make enough room for the expanded patch code.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Small in-memory machine code patches can be manually applied with the system debug utility, such as CP/M's DDT or MS-DOS's DEBUG debuggers.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Programmers working in interpreted BASIC often used the POKE command to alter the functionality of a system service routine or the interpreter itself.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] A patch for source code defines how to modify the text of code files.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Such a patch is usually a text file that encodes the differences between two versions of a file.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] As this type of patch is often created via the `diff` command, the patch file is also a diff file.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Source code patching is common for an open-source software project.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] Maintainers receive patches or people publish patches that fix problems and add functionality, like support for local languages outside the project's locale.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] In an example from the early development of the Linux kernel (noted for publishing its complete source code), Linus Torvalds, the original author, received hundreds of thousands of patches from many programmers to apply against his original version.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] The Apache HTTP Server originally evolved as a number of patches that Brian Behlendorf collated to improve NCSA HTTPd, hence a name that implies that it is a collection of patches ("a patchy server").
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] The FAQ on the project's official site states that the name 'Apache' was chosen from respect for the Native American Indian tribe of Apache.
[src:over-the-air-updates/patch-computing] However, the 'a patchy server' explanation was initially given on the project's website.
[src:over-the-air-updates/rollback-data-management] In database technologies, a **rollback** is an operation which returns the database to some previous state.
[src:over-the-air-updates/rollback-data-management] Rollbacks are important for database integrity, because they mean that the database can be restored to a clean copy even after erroneous operations are performed.
[src:over-the-air-updates/rollback-data-management] They are crucial for recovering from database server crashes; by rolling back any transaction which was active at the time of the crash, the database is restored to a consistent state.
[src:over-the-air-updates/rollback-data-management] The rollback feature is usually implemented with a transaction log, but can also be implemented via multiversion concurrency control.
[src:over-the-air-updates/rollback-data-management] A cascading rollback occurs in database systems when a transaction (T1) causes a failure and a rollback must be performed.
[src:over-the-air-updates/rollback-data-management] Other transactions dependent on T1's actions must also be rollbacked due to T1's failure, thus causing a cascading effect.
[src:over-the-air-updates/rollback-data-management] That is, one transaction's failure causes many to fail.
[src:over-the-air-updates/rollback-data-management] Practical database recovery techniques guarantee cascadeless rollback, therefore a cascading rollback is not a desirable result.
[src:over-the-air-updates/rollback-data-management] SQL refers to Structured Query Language, a kind of language used to access, update and manipulate database.
[src:over-the-air-updates/rollback-data-management] In SQL, `ROLLBACK` is a command that causes all data changes since the last `START TRANSACTION` or `BEGIN` to be discarded by the relational database management systems (RDBMS), so that the state of the data is "rolled back" to the way it was before those changes were made.
[src:over-the-air-updates/rollback-data-management] A `ROLLBACK` statement will also release any existing savepoints that may be in use.
[src:over-the-air-updates/rollback-data-management] In most SQL dialects, `ROLLBACK`s are connection specific.
[src:over-the-air-updates/rollback-data-management] This means that if two connections are made to the same database, a `ROLLBACK` made in one connection will not affect any other connections.
[src:over-the-air-updates/rollback-data-management] Rollbacks are not exclusive to databases: any stateful distributed system may use rollback operations to maintain consistency.
[src:over-the-air-updates/rollback-data-management] Examples of distributed systems that can support rollbacks include message queues and workflow management systems.
[src:over-the-air-updates/rollback-data-management] More generally, any operation that resets a system to its previous state before another operation or series of operations can be viewed as a rollback.
